<section xml:id="section-assignment3">
  <title>Assignment 3</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write these cartesian loci as polar loci. (6) 
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            x - 4y = 1
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            x^2 + 2y^2 = 3
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \frac{y}{x} - 3 \frac{y^2}{x^2} = 3
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Write these cartesian loci as spherical loci. (6) 
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            5x - 4y + 6z = 1
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            x^2 + y^2 + z^2 - \sqrt{x^2 + y^2} = 1
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \left(\frac{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}{z}\right)^3 - x^2 - y^2 - z^2
            = 1
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this parametric curve (in cartesian coordinates). (6) 
        <me>
          \gamma(t) = (x(t), y(t)) = (\cos 6\pi t, \sin 6\pi
            t)
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            Find <m>\gamma(0)</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Determine the length of the curve on <m>t \in [0,4]</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Determine the behaviour of the curve as <m>t \rightarrow
            \infty</m>. 
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this parametric curve (in cartesian coordinates). (6) 
        <me>
          \gamma(t) = (x(t), y(t)) = \left(4, \frac{1}{(t+1)^2} \right)
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            Find <m>\gamma(0)</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Determine the length of the curve on <m>t \in [0,4]</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Determine the behaviour of the curve as <m>t \rightarrow
            \infty</m>. 
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this parametric curve (in polar coordinates). (4) 
        <me>
          \gamma(t) = (r(t), \theta(t)) = (t+1,t)
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            Find <m>\gamma(0)</m>.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Determine the behaviour of the curve as <m>t \rightarrow
            \infty</m>. 
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this parametric curve. (6) 
        <me>
          \gamma(t) = (x(t), y(t), z(t)) = (t, t^2, t^3)
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            Determine the intersection (if any) of the curve with the
            unit sphere.
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Determine the intersection (if any) of the curve the the
            cube with vertices <m>(\pm 1, \pm 1, \pm 1)</m>. 
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this parametric curve. (6) 
        <me>
          \gamma(t) = (x(t), y(t), z(t)) = (\sqrt{t^2+1}, t, t^2-2)
        </me>
        <ol>
          <li><p>
            Determine the intersection (if any) of the curve with the
            unit sphere. (Approximsate values calculated by computer
            are fine.) 
          </p></li>
          <li><p>
            Determine the intersection (if any )of the curve the the
            cube with vertices <m>(\pm 1, \pm 1, \pm 1)</m>. 
          </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Parametrize the following curve by arclength for <m>t > 0</m>.
        (8)
        <me>
          \gamma(t) = (t^3, t^3 + t^2, t^3 -t^2)
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
